        "assistant_drafted_requirements_summary": "Expose only governed Notion capabilities to agents: The product must provide an ANIP fronting service for Notion that exposes only bounded capabilities for workspace search, database query, page creation preparation, page update preparation, and comment preparation. Agents must not receive raw Notion API access, raw workspace tools, or MCP as their execution surface.\nKeep read operations scoped and summary-only: Workspace search and database query must be read-only, limited to allowed workspace, page, and database boundaries, and return actor-visible summarized context rather than raw exports. Result limits must be supported, and provider-specific options may be allowed only when they remain bounded and do not bypass scope or approval policy.\nStop page and comment changes at preview before mutation: Page creation, page updates, and comments must be handled as preparation flows that generate previews only. The system must not create pages, apply updates, or post comments as part of these capabilities. Any actual mutation must remain approval-gated beyond the preview step.\nRequire explicit identifiers and return clarification-required when context is missing: The product must require explicit inputs for governed operations, including workspace scope for workspace search, database ID for database query, parent ID for page creation preparation, page ID for page update preparation and comment preparation, and the relevant query or summary fields for each flow. When required page, database, parent, workspace scope, or query context is missing or ambiguous, the system must return clarification-required rather than guessing.\nDeny unsafe or out-of-bound Notion actions: The product must deny requests that would expose private pages, hidden pages, raw workspace export, workspace administration, arbitrary block mutation, parent override, or any unapproved mutation. Backend options may support bounded provider controls such as selected properties, page size, or safe filter fragments, but must not expand access or bypass governance.\nPreserve governance visibility through scope, approvals, and audit: The service must operate with actor-visible scope controls, approval records for change flows, and auditability sufficient for governance review. The deployment posture should support centralized enforcement of allowlists, visibility boundaries, and reviewable outcomes for both bounded reads and denied or approval-stopped actions."
      }
    }
